evaluation.significance_reason:
Fine-tuning small-scale LLMs on GSM8K is currently bottlenecked by update budgets (≤4 k) and GPU hours.
According to the proposal, FLORA
• lifts 5-shot GSM8K accuracy from 75 % (NOAH) to 79 % at 1 k steps – a sizeable +4 pp that closes ~30 % of the remaining gap to SOTA while using the same model size (0.6 B) and no extra data;
• reduces wall-clock by 6 % and energy by 22 % versus NOAH owing to cheaper probes and LR reuse;
• enables seamless switching between LoRA ranks (8–64) without re-tuning, which is valuable for many‐task workflows and hyper-parameter sweeps.
Because LoRA is the de-facto PEFT standard, a rank-aware scheduler that is both faster and more accurate could be adopted widely beyond Qwen3, impacting everyday fine-tuning practice.  The improvement margins (time, energy, accuracy) are meaningful though not revolutionary.

